SIMPLE: prospective
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prospective
<hw>Pro*spec"tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>prospectivus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>prospectif</ets>. See
<er>Prospect</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or
pertaining to a prospect; furnishing a prospect; perspective.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Time's long and dark <qex>prospective</qex> glass.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Looking forward in time; acting with foresight; --
opposed to <ant>retrospective</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The French king of Sweden are circumspect, industrious, and
<qex>prospective</qex>, too, in this affair.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J.
Child.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Being within view or consideration, as a future
event or contingency; relating to the future: expected; <as>as, a
<ex>prospective</ex> benefit</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Points on which the promises, at the time of ordination, had no
<qex>prospective</qex> bearing.</q> <rj><qau>W. Jay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prospective</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prospective
<hw>Pro*spec"tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
scene before or around, in time or in space; view; prospect.</def>
<rj><au>Sir H. Wotton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A perspective glass.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer. Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prospectively</ent>⟦br⟧
